The JeuneS3 programme is a partnership framework aligned with the Dutch SRHR policy with a focus on young people (especially girls) and key populations in francophone fragile countries or areas in Africa. The partnership will start working in Cameroon, Central African Republic and the Democratic Republic of Congo and intends to expand in the second year to Benin

Overall: To ensure that young people (YP), especially girls, and key populations are able, motivated and have the opportunity to make informed choices about their sexual and reproductive health (SRH) and that their sexual and reproductive rights are respected. Pathways: 1. YP are respected as important stakeholders in policy formulation and programs on YP SRHR 2. YP are able to make informed decisions about their SRHR 3. YP and KP are able and have the opportunity to use responsive SRH services 4. Social, cultural, legal, policy and gender barriers around YP’s and KP’s SRHR are reduced

Overall objective: support the implementation of UNISDR's Sendai Framework for Disaster Risk Reduction, and SDG's 11, 13, 15, to ensure that vulnerable people become more resilient to crises in the face of climate change and environmental degradation. Strategic objectives: ensure increased community resilience through: 1. strengthening partner NGO's and communities in their knowledge and their dialogue capacity on Integrated Risk Management (IRM); 2. embarking on specific IRM dialogue trajectories at local, national and regional levels, focusing on 3 domains: Policy, Investment and Practise

According to the Humanitarian Response Plan 2016, there are humanitarian needs across South Sudan as a result of multiple and interlocking threats, including armed conflict and inter-communal violence, economic decline, disease, and climactic shocks. It is estimated that these threats affect at least 9.6 million people, including an estimated 8.2 4 million in need of humanitarian assistance

An inclusive and peaceful Niger delta, based on equity and sustainable development, in which local communties manage their natural resources effectively for sustainable green growth, and where the space for negotiations between communities, government and companies on oil impact and oil management is institutionalized.
As continuation of the previous Joint Responses in South Sudan, in this one Cordaid will implement a humanitarian program in the sectors of Food Security and Livelihood, cash and WASH.

After the earthquake and tsunami in Sulawesi end September 2018 CRS partnered with Cordaid to provide emergency response with the DRA acute mechanism. The needs and response are currently transitioning to recovery. CRS and Cordaid both contribute to this recovery program. CRS will provide multi- purpose cash for recovery on the short term (ending March 2019 because of SHO demand to spend 50 % first 6 months) and DRR on the longer term. Project runs until June 2020.

A stable, peaceful and equitable society in fragile countries in which: Local women and women’s organizations and youth and youth organizations are able to influence and meaningfully participate in decision-making processes, specifically those related to peacebuilding; Security and justice provision is people-centered and security and justice institutions are effective, inclusive and accountable; A resilient health system is in place, contributing to Universal Health Coverage; A sustainable, diversified economy benefits local communities

A violence free society where women are empowered to participate in nation building • A Peaceful, diverse society that promotes good governance and the rule of law • A peaceful and stable South Sudan with transparent and sustainable resource management for the benefit of all citizens

As part of the 3rd Dutch National Action Plan 1325, this 3-year program establishes an effective partnership between Dutch and Libyan NGO's. It contributes to the general objective of the Netherlands NAP 1325 to contribute to an enabling environment for women's participation and empowerment in conflict and post-conflict environments, so they can meaningfully participate in conflict prevention, resolution, peace building, protection, relief and recovery. The program aims to deepen local partnerships through capacity building, programming, knowledge sharing and lobby and advocacy. Learning and critical reflection through plenary workshops will strengthen the collective efforts to enable Libyan women and men to play their role as bridge builders in their community
